---
import CTAButton from "./CTAButton.astro";

const headlineStats = [
  {
    value: "92.2%",
    label: "of identifiable alumni outcomes were clearly or probably CS-related",
    detail: "153 of 166 identifiable current outcomes were classified as clearly or probably CS-related."
  },
  {
    value: "49.4%",
    label: "were in software engineering or closely related roles",
    detail: "Software engineering was the single largest outcome area in the LinkedIn-based review."
  },
  {
    value: "59.1%",
    label: "appear to be career switchers into CS",
    detail: "104 of 176 reviewed profiles appeared to represent clear or likely career switches into computing."
  },
  {
    value: "76.0%",
    label: "began a first visible technical role before or during graduation year",
    detail: "Among classifiable cases, many alumni reached internships, apprenticeships, or technical roles while still completing the degree."
  }
];

const careerDirections = [
  "Software engineering and application development",
  "Web, full-stack, and product development",
  "Data analytics, data science, AI, machine learning, and NLP-related work",
  "Systems, cloud, cybersecurity, technical operations, and network engineering",
  "Research computing, bioinformatics, education, consulting, and public-sector technical work",
  "Technical leadership, founder roles, and hybrid technical roles"
];

const industrySectors = [
  { name: "Technology and Software", count: 40, percent: "24.1%" },
  { name: "Education and Research", count: 20, percent: "12.0%" },
  { name: "Energy, Transportation, and Manufacturing", count: 19, percent: "11.4%" },
  { name: "Aerospace, Defense, and Engineering", count: 17, percent: "10.2%" },
  { name: "Finance and Business Services", count: 17, percent: "10.2%" },
  { name: "Retail, Consumer, and Media", count: 16, percent: "9.6%" },
  { name: "Healthcare and Biotechnology", count: 13, percent: "7.8%" },
  { name: "Consulting and Professional Services", count: 11, percent: "6.6%" },
  { name: "Government and Public Sector", count: 7, percent: "4.2%" },
  { name: "Startups and Innovation", count: 6, percent: "3.6%" }
];

const employerGroups = [
  {
    title: "Technology and Software",
    employers: ["Amazon", "Google", "Microsoft", "Salesforce", "Handshake", "CrowdStrike", "Canonical", "Workiva"]
  },
  {
    title: "Aerospace, Defense, and Engineering",
    employers: ["Lockheed Martin", "Northrop Grumman", "Boeing", "Blue Origin", "Raytheon", "United Launch Alliance", "Maxar Technologies"]
  },
  {
    title: "Finance, Business, and Consulting",
    employers: ["Charles Schwab", "Capital One", "American Express", "Deloitte", "RSM", "Publicis Sapient", "Slalom Build"]
  },
  {
    title: "Education, Research, and Healthcare",
    employers: ["University of Colorado Boulder", "Carnegie Mellon University", "University of Utah", "Michigan Medicine", "Roche", "AbbVie", "Cleveland Clinic"]
  },
  {
    title: "Consumer, Media, and Other Industries",
    employers: ["Nike", "DIRECTV", "Chewy", "PGA Tour", "Ibotta", "Levi Strauss & Co", "Hudl"]
  },
  {
    title: "Government, Public Sector, and Civic Tech",
    employers: ["NOAA", "City of Grand Junction", "City of Burlington, Vermont", "Hack for LA", "BI Incorporated"]
  }
];

const supportItems = [
  {
    title: "Career services",
    body: "CSPB students can use CU Boulder career resources, including resume and interview support, Handshake, career events, and employer-facing services."
  },
  {
    title: "Projects and portfolio evidence",
    body: "Course projects, team projects, GitHub repositories, technical writing, and workplace projects can help students show what they can actually build and explain."
  },
  {
    title: "Prior experience as an asset",
    body: "Many post-bacc students bring experience from another field. That prior domain knowledge can become part of a stronger technical story, especially in areas such as healthcare, finance, education, research, engineering, media, government, or business."
  },
  {
    title: "Graduate-study planning",
    body: "Some students use CSPB to prepare for graduate study in computer science, data science, computational linguistics, network engineering, or related areas."
  }
];
---

<section class="stack">
  <div>
    <p class="kicker">LinkedIn-based alumni snapshot</p>
    <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">CSPB outcomes are broader than one job title</h2>
    <p class="lede mt-4">
      This page draws on a LinkedIn-based review of 180 CSPB graduates, with 166 profiles that had identifiable current LinkedIn-visible status. It should be read as a hand-reviewed alumni snapshot rather than an official university placement report, but the overall pattern is still useful: alumni show up in software, data, systems, research, education, consulting, public-sector work, graduate study, and other CS-related areas.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-4">
    {headlineStats.map((stat) => (
      <article class="card card-pad">
        <p class="text-3xl font-black tracking-tight text-neutral-950">{stat.value}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm font-bold leading-6 text-neutral-700">{stat.label}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-xs leading-5 text-neutral-500">{stat.detail}</p>
      </article>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<section class="stack">
  <div>
    <p class="kicker">Role directions</p>
    <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">Common directions alumni pursue</h2>
    <p class="lede mt-4">
      Software engineering is the largest single pathway in the reviewed LinkedIn dataset, but it is not the whole story. CSPB alumni use computing across many kinds of organizations and roles.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid gap-3 md:grid-cols-2">
    {careerDirections.map((direction) => (
      <article class="rounded-[1.25rem] border border-neutral-200 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-neutral-950">{direction}</p>
      </article>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<section class="stack">
  <div>
    <p class="kicker">Industry sectors</p>
    <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">Alumni work across many sectors</h2>
    <p class="lede mt-4">
      Technology and software is the largest single sector in the dataset, but most identifiable alumni outcomes appear outside that category. That is part of what makes post-baccalaureate outcomes interesting: many students combine computing with prior professional or disciplinary experience.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="card overflow-hidden">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-[minmax(0,1fr)_auto_auto] gap-x-4 border-b border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 px-5 py-3 text-sm font-black text-neutral-700">
      <div>Industry sector</div>
      <div>Alumni</div>
      <div>Percent</div>
    </div>

    {industrySectors.map((sector) => (
      <div class="grid grid-cols-[minmax(0,1fr)_auto_auto] gap-x-4 border-b border-neutral-100 px-5 py-4 text-sm last:border-b-0">
        <div class="font-bold text-neutral-900">{sector.name}</div>
        <div class="text-neutral-600">{sector.count}</div>
        <div class="font-black text-neutral-900">{sector.percent}</div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<section class="stack">
  <div>
    <p class="kicker">Selected employers</p>
    <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">The employer list makes the outcomes concrete</h2>
    <p class="lede mt-4">
      The reviewed dataset includes alumni in roles across major technology firms, aerospace and defense, finance, education, healthcare, consumer companies, and public-sector organizations.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid gap-4 xl:grid-cols-2">
    {employerGroups.map((group) => (
      <section class="card card-pad">
        <h3 class="heading-md">{group.title}</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          {group.employers.map((employer) => (
            <span class="rounded-full border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 px-3 py-2 text-sm font-bold text-neutral-800">
              {employer}
            </span>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    ))}
  </div>

  <section class="rounded-[1.25rem] border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 px-5 py-4 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
    Selected employers are drawn from LinkedIn-visible roles in this hand-collected dataset. Presence does not imply employer endorsement, partnership, or guaranteed placement.
  </section>
</section>

<section class="card card-pad">
  <div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[1.15fr_0.85fr] lg:items-start">
    <div>
      <p class="kicker">Career changers and career advancers</p>
      <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">The program serves more than one kind of student</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
        Many alumni appear to be career changers moving into software, data, systems, or related technical work. Others were already in or near the field and used CSPB to strengthen credentials, formalize their background, broaden their options, or prepare for graduate study.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
        That mix matters. The degree does not serve only one outcome story. For some students, it is a bridge into a first technical role. For others, it is a way to deepen capability, make a role shift inside a company, or become a stronger candidate for the next step.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-[1.25rem] bg-neutral-950 p-5 text-white">
      <p class="text-4xl font-black text-[#cfb87c]">34.1%</p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm font-bold leading-6 text-white/80">
        were already in or adjacent to the field
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-xs leading-5 text-white/60">
        This includes alumni already in CS, software, IT, CS-adjacent roles, or using CSPB for advancement, credentialing, or further study.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="stack">
  <div>
    <p class="kicker">Career preparation</p>
    <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">The degree is strongest when paired with visible evidence of ability</h2>
    <p class="lede mt-4">
      CSPB gives students a structured CS foundation and a CU Boulder credential. Career preparation also depends on the evidence students build while they are in the program.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="auto-grid">
    {supportItems.map((item) => (
      <article class="card card-pad">
        <h3 class="heading-md">{item.title}</h3>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">{item.body}</p>
      </article>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card card-pad">
  <div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[1.2fr_0.8fr] lg:items-start">
    <div>
      <p class="kicker">Graduate study</p>
      <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">Graduate school can also be an outcome</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
        Some students use the Computer Science Post-Baccalaureate Program to prepare for graduate study in computer science, data science, computational linguistics, network engineering, or related fields. For eligible students, post-baccalaureate accelerated master’s options may also be worth discussing with advising.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
        PBAM options are not the main purpose of CSPB, and some graduate work is expected to be completed on the Boulder campus. Students considering that route should review the Apply / Next Steps module and speak with advising.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-5">
        <CTAButton href="/modules/apply-next-steps/" label="Review graduate planning notes" variant="dark" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-[1.25rem] border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-5">
      <p class="kicker">Possible next step</p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm font-bold leading-6 text-neutral-700">
        Use CSPB to strengthen your undergraduate CS foundation before evaluating graduate programs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card card-pad border-l-4 border-l-[#cfb87c]">
  <p class="kicker">Job market note</p>
  <h2 class="heading-md mt-2">The market changes, but the foundation still matters</h2>
  <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
    The software and computing job market changes over time. AI tools, hiring cycles, entry-level competition, and regional labor markets all affect what students experience. A CS degree can strengthen a student’s foundation and credentials, but the strongest career story usually combines the degree with projects, internships, workplace experience, GitHub repositories, technical communication, and interview preparation.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
    For many CSPB students, the distinctive advantage is not starting from zero. It is adding computer science to a previous degree, prior work experience, and a developing portfolio of technical work.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="stack">
  <div>
    <p class="kicker">Next steps</p>
    <h2 class="heading-lg mt-2">Explore how the program supports your goals</h2>
  </div>

  <div class="auto-grid">
    <article class="card card-pad">
      <h3 class="heading-md">Review the curriculum</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
        Start with the courses and curriculum pathways to see how the degree builds technical foundations.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-5">
        <CTAButton href="/modules/curriculum/" label="Explore curriculum" variant="dark" />
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="card card-pad">
      <h3 class="heading-md">Use student support</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
        Review advising, career resources, tutoring, course support, and community resources.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-5">
        <CTAButton href="/modules/student-support/" label="Review support" variant="dark" />
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="card card-pad">
      <h3 class="heading-md">Think about fit</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-neutral-600">
        If you are still deciding, compare your goals with the right-fit module.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-5">
        <CTAButton href="/modules/is-cspb-right-for-me/" label="Check fit" variant="dark" />
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>
